Win.Dropper.Gh0stRAT-9980455-1.description: Gh0stRAT is a well-known family of remote access trojans designed to provide an attacker with complete control over an infected system. Capabilities include monitoring keystrokes, collecting video footage from the webcam, and uploading/executing follow-on malware. The source code for Gh0stRAT has been publicly available on the Internet for years, significantly lowering the barrier for actors to modify and reuse the code in new attacks.

Win.Dropper.HawkEye-9980407-0.description: Hawkeye is an information stealing malware that specifically targets usernames and passwords stored by web browsers and mail clients on an infected machine. It is commonly spread via email and can also propagate through removable media.

Win.Dropper.Lokibot-9980537-1.description: Lokibot is an information-stealing malware designed to siphon off sensitive information stored on an infected device. It is modular in nature, supporting the ability to steal sensitive information from a number of popular applications. It is commonly pushed via malicious documents delivered via spam emails.

Win.Dropper.Nanocore-9980555-0.description: Nanocore is a .NET remote access trojan. Its source code has been leaked several times, making it widely available. Like other RATs, it allows full control of the system, including recording video and audio, stealing passwords, downloading files and recording keystrokes.

Win.Dropper.njRAT-9980427-0.description: njRAT, also known as Bladabindi, is a remote access trojan (RAT) that allows attackers to execute commands on the infected host, log keystrokes and remotely turn on the victim's webcam and microphone. njRAT was developed by the Sparclyheason group. Some of the largest attacks using this malware date back to 2014.

Win.Packed.Upatre-9980519-1.description: Upatre is a malicious downloader often used by exploit kits and phishing campaigns. Upatre downloads and executes malicious executables, such as banking malware.

Win.Ransomware.Cerber-9980410-0.description: Cerber is ransomware that encrypts documents, photos, databases and other important files. Historically, this malware would replace files with encrypted versions and add the file extension ".cerber," although in more recent campaigns other file extensions are used.

Win.Ransomware.TeslaCrypt-9980413-0.description: TeslaCrypt is a well-known ransomware family that encrypts a user's files with strong encryption and demands Bitcoin in exchange for a file decryption service. A flaw in the encryption algorithm was discovered that allowed files to be decrypted without paying the ransomware, and eventually, the malware developers released the master key allowing all encrypted files to be recovered easily.
